{
  "title": "Documenting Cron-Driven Tasks Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to implement and document cron-driven tasks using the FastAPI framework in Python 3.12+. The example provided here utilizes a timer-based approach, `aiohttp_cron`, to manage recurring tasks.",
  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is a modern, efficient, and intuitive web framework for building APIs.",
    "Aiohttp_cron is an extension for aiohttp that allows the creation of timer-based tasks.",
    "In this example, we will document a simple cron task to fetch data from an API and update a database.",
    "Python 3.12+ features such as async/await are utilized for efficient task handling."
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException\nimport aiohttp\nfrom aiohttp_cron import cron\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\ncron.aiohttp.set_executor(\naiohttp.ClientRunner(connector=aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=16)))\n\ncron.aiohttp.crontab(\"* * * * *\", job_func=fetch_data)\n\ndef fetch_data():\n    async with aiohttp.get('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1') as resp:\n        data = await resp.text()\n        if not data:\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=500, detail='Failed to fetch data')\n    # Database update logic goes here \n```"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "This example is compatible with FastAPI version 0.64.0 and Python 3.12+.",
    "It uses aiohttp_cron version 17.0.0 which supports Python 3.12+."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "The example provided only demonstrates the implementation of a basic cron-driven task and does not include actual database update logic.",
    "Make sure to replace the API URL with your desired API endpoint in the code.",
    "This example uses `HTTPException` for error handling, which is specific to FastAPI."
  ]
}
